### Patients

A total of 3045 patients were enrolled at 703 separate sites across the United States. Of these patients, 2716 completed the study protocol and provided data for analysis of efficacy and safety of the treatment. The main reasons for noncompletion of the protocol were as follows: 177 (5.8% of the total patients enrolled) were lost to follow-up or declined to continue the study; 17 (0.06%) because of lack of efficacy; 117 (3.8%) because of adverse events; and 56 (1.8%) for miscellaneous or unknown reasons.

The principal clinical characteristics of the patients who completed this study are listed in Table 1. There was an almost equal distribution of men and women. Approximately three-quarters of the patients were white and 13.3% were African American. Patients not receiving treatment for hypertension at study entry (untreated group) or the group that was treated but uncontrolled, had similar {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }}. Patients who entered the study designated as controlled had substantially lower (and normal) {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} values.

